		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Augusta Ga.</placeName> <date>21st Apr. 5626</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Rev I Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Since my last&#44; the &#8220;Occident&#44;&#8221; from<lb/> the commencement of the present volume&#44; has reached<lb/> me by mail. In the <date>June</date> No. I notice some very<lb/> kind remarks about me&#44; which claim my earnest<lb/> thanks.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I have obtained two more subscribers<lb/> from <persName>Mrs Mordercai Hyams</persName> &#38; <persName>Mr Morris Cohen</persName>&#44; to<lb/> whom please forward the Nos. from No. 1 of the current year.<lb/> I shall continue my endeavors to promote the circulation<lb/> of the Occident in this city&#44; <del>the</del> but I apprehend I have<lb/> pretty much touched the limits. Possibly I may yet be<lb/> able to influence one or two more.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I am laboring diligently in the little<lb/> field in which I now find myself&#44; where I must confess<lb/> I do not find Religion or Knowing as I could desire. Mam&#45;<lb/>mon has stronger claims&#44; &#38; greater influence than <sic>Adonay</sic>.<lb/>  &#8220;&#39;Tis true &#39;tis pity&#44; and pity &#39;tis &#39;tis true.&#8221;Again&#44; I perceive<lb/> a tendency among several to go astray after the strange god&#44;<lb/> which you have characteristically termed &#8220;the modern hybrid&#44;&#8221;</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>but as long as I remain here&#44; I am determined it shall<lb/> make no headway&#44; by following the simple rule. Withstand<lb/> at the beginning. This for your uneducated eye. Our<lb/> friend of the Messenger went a step too far in publishing<lb/> a private letter to him&#44; which annoyed me a little&#44; tho<lb/> the matter was hardly worth notice. At the breaking out<lb/> of the War&#44; he became so political and violent in his crusade against<lb/> the <placeName>South</placeName> that I abandoned the agency of the paper and<lb/> even my continuance as a subscriber in a letter which<lb/> was rather caustic. With the return of peace&#44; I wished to<lb/> remit him the subscription which I owed&#44; and at same<lb/> time to introduce a gentleman from <placeName>Augusta</placeName> who <del>wished</del><lb/> required some Tallethoth&#44; and whilst doing so&#44; in the <sic>fulness</sic><lb/> of my heart&#44; and in deference to his years and long services<lb/> I held out freely the olive branch. He ought to have drawn<lb/> the deliberate line of demarcation between this&#44; and the<lb/> topics I added on general Jewish making here.  However<lb/> <add>Hebrew</add> It is hardly worth notice indeed.</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">With kind regards&#44; participated in<lb/> by  <persName>Mrs Jacobs</persName>&#44; believe me</p>
			<p rend="indent(10)">yours faithfully</p>
			<p rend="indent(11)"><persName role="author">Henry S. Jacobs</persName></p>
		</body>
